// Quick-start profile selection. Sets sensible defaults for many
// settings throughout the rest of the installer. The user can still
// fine-tune every option later in the «Configuration Categories» menu;
// the profile only changes which checkboxes start out checked, it does
// not hide any choice.
//
// Exactly one of these five settings will be #true at any time
// (radiolist semantics). All other Ditana settings reference these
// flags from their `default-value` expressions.

- name="profile-default" \
  dialog-name="User Profile" \
  short-description="Standard - Recommended Ditana defaults" \
  long-description="""
Standard: The recommended profile for users who want Ditana's curated experience without further customization. Equivalent to leaving the original Ditana defaults untouched: a privacy-focused FOSS setup with sensible choices across the board.
""" \
  spdx-identifiers="" \
  default-value=#true {
    arch-packages ""
}

- name="profile-windows" \
  dialog-name="User Profile" \
  short-description="Coming from KDE Plasma, Cinnamon, Xfce or MATE" \
  long-description="""
Coming from KDE Plasma, Cinnamon, Xfce or MATE: Geared towards users migrating from a traditional menu / panel layout - Windows, but equally KDE Plasma, Cinnamon, Xfce, or MATE.

Defaults shift towards applications and conventions that should feel more familiar coming from such environments. Ditana's privacy-focused, FOSS-first character is preserved; only individual application choices and a handful of settings differ from Standard.
""" \
  spdx-identifiers="" \
  default-value=#false {
    arch-packages ""
}

- name="profile-developer" \
  dialog-name="User Profile" \
  short-description="Software Developer - Dev-friendly defaults" \
  long-description="""
Software Developer: Optimised for software development work.

Additional editor tooling is preinstalled and several settings useful for debugging are enabled (such as unrestricted ptrace and core dumps). A handful of options normally hidden under «Advanced Settings» are pulled forward so you encounter them up front - they remain available in their normal location too, so you can still revise without «Back».
""" \
  spdx-identifiers="" \
  default-value=#false {
    arch-packages ""
}

- name="profile-server" \
  dialog-name="User Profile" \
  short-description="Server - Headless system, no graphical interface" \
  long-description="""
Server (for headless installations): virtual machines used as build hosts, home servers, NAS guests on hypervisors such as Synology / Proxmox, and similar setups.

No desktop environment, no browser, no office suite, no terminal emulator package. All other Ditana defaults are unchanged - including LTS-kernel ZFS, automatic snapshots, firewalld, and the SSH server.

Ditana intentionally does not preinstall any specific server software here (no nginx, no database, no container runtime); it is not specified what kind of server this will become.
""" \
  spdx-identifiers="" \
  default-value=#false {
    arch-packages ""
}

- name="profile-quick" \
  dialog-name="User Profile" \
  short-description="Quick Installation - Fastest install (for distro hopping)" \
  long-description="""
Quick Installation: Trades several Ditana-specific features for the shortest install time. Use this if you only want to evaluate Ditana, not work in it long-term - the typical «distro-hopping» scenario.

The slowest install steps are skipped or replaced with faster alternatives, mostly around filesystem choice, browser, and locally-hosted AI. All four desktop environments stay preselected so you can compare them in the same system - a few extra packages cost little compared to the items above.

Note: this profile optimises install duration, not the resulting system. The defaults sacrificed here are exactly what distinguishes Ditana from a generic Arch derivative. If you intend to use Ditana as a daily driver, pick «Standard» instead.
""" \
  spdx-identifiers="" \
  default-value=#false {
    arch-packages ""
}
